# Line endings are a correctness constraint in this repository, not a style
# preference.
#
# Two things break on a CRLF checkout, and neither failure names the real cause:
#
#   1. Shebang scripts that run inside the Linux container. Git for Windows
#      checks out CRLF by default, so `#!/usr/bin/env bash` becomes
#      `#!/usr/bin/env bash\r` and the kernel looks for an interpreter literally
#      named "bash\r". The image build dies with
#      `/usr/bin/env: 'bash\r': No such file or directory`, and
#      docker/entrypoint.sh fails the same way at container start.
#
#   2. The byte-exact gates. golden-check pins each b1/ oracle page's SVG output
#      by SHA-256, and the schema/manifest/status generators are diffed against
#      their committed output. A platform-dependent line ending makes those
#      comparisons platform-dependent too.
#
# So: normalize everything to LF in the repository *and* in the working tree, on
# every platform. Editors have handled LF on Windows for years; a corrupted
# shebang is not similarly forgiving.
* text=auto eol=lf

# Byte-exact artifacts: git must not touch these AT ALL, in either direction.
# golden-check pins each b1/ oracle page by SHA-256 and corpus-check verifies
# archived files against a hash lockfile, so "harmless" normalisation of a line
# ending is a gate failure. `-text` disables conversion entirely; it is not the
# same as `eol=lf`, which would still rewrite them once.
tests/golden/**            -text
tests/fixtures/corpus/**   -text

# Belt and braces for the files where a CRLF slip is fatal rather than cosmetic.
*.sh        text eol=lf
bin/*       text eol=lf
docker/*    text eol=lf
plugin/bin/* text eol=lf

# Never touched: git must not "normalize" bytes that are not text.
*.png  binary
*.jpg  binary
*.jpeg binary
*.gif  binary
*.webp binary
*.pdf  binary
*.ico  binary
*.woff binary
*.woff2 binary
*.ttf  binary
*.otf  binary
*.tar  binary
*.fp   binary
